Wash and dry all produce. Core, seed, and thinly slice the @red bell pepper{1}. Thinly slice the @yellow bell pepper{1}. Thinly slice the @button mushrooms{4%ounce}. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}. Core, then dice the @roma tomato{1}. Strip the @rosemary{¼%ounce} from the sprigs and roughly chop 1 teaspoon.

> Paella, the national dish of Spain, is famous for its socarrat, the crispy crust that develops on the bottom of the pan.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add the mushrooms and cook, tossing for ~{4-5%minutes}, until golden brown. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Remove from the pan and set aside.

Heat another drizzle of oil in the same pan over medium-high heat. Add the bell peppers and tomato to the pan and cook, tossing for ~{3-4%minutes}, until softened. Add the garlic, chopped rosemary, 1/2 teaspoon @turmeric{1%teaspoon}, and 1/2 teaspoon @smoked paprika{1%teaspoon} to the pan. Cook for another ~{1-2%minutes}, until fragrant. Season with salt and pepper.

> This version is flavored with woodsy rosemary and smoky paprika for a unique flavor. Vibrant turmeric adds gorgeous color.

Add the @basmati rice{¾%cup} and mushrooms, to the pan and toss to coat in a drizzle of oil. Stir @water{2%cups}, a large pinch of salt, and the @veggie stock concentrate{1} into the pan. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a low simmer for ~{15-20%minutes}, until the liquid is absorbed and the rice is tender.

> HINT: Don't stir the paella as it cooks! It's the secret to a crispy crust. If your paella hasn't formed a crust by the time the liquid is absorbed, you can increase the heat to high for a couple minutes.

Take the vegetarian paella off the heat and cover with a #kitchen towel{} to steam for ~{5%minutes}. Cut the @lemon{1} into wedges and serve on the side for an added burst of citrus. Enjoy!